'''Alan Tuffin''' (born 2 August 1933) is a [[British people|British]] former [[trade union]] leader.

Tuffin attended Eltham Secondary School, leaving aged sixteen to work for the [[Post Office]].  He became active in the [[Union of Communication Workers]], as its London Union Regional Official in 1957, then taking a full-time post as National Official in 1969, and becoming Deputy General Secretary ten years later.  In 1982, he was elected as General Secretary of the union.<ref name="whoswho">"[http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U38151/TUFFIN_Alan_David TUFFIN, Alan David]", ''[[Who's Who]]''</ref>

From 1982 until his retirement in 1993, Tuffin served on the General Council of the [[Trades Union Congress]] (TUC), winning election as [[President of the TUC]] in 1992/93.  In 1993, he was also made a commander of the [[Order of the British Empire]].  In retirement, he has served on the [[Employment Appeal Tribunal]], and as a director of [[Remploy]].<ref name="whoswho" />

